==English==

===Etymology===
{{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|acoustumer|lang=fro}}, {{term|acustumer|lang=fro}} (Modern French {{term|accoutumer|lang=fr}}) corresponding to {{term|a||to, toward|lang=fro}} + {{term|coustume|lang=fro|custom}}. More at {{term|custom|lang=en}}, {{term|costume|lang=en}}. Compare {{etyl|oc|en}} {{term|acostumar|lang=oc}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/ə.ˈkəs.təm/}}
* {{audio|en-us-accustom.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To make familiar by use; to cause to accept; to habituate, familiarize, or inure; -- with ''to''.
#* ca. '''1753:''' [[w:John Hawkesworth|John Hawkesworth]] ''et al.'', ''Adventurer''
#*: I shall always fear that he who '''accustoms''' himself to fraud in little things, wants only opportunity to practice it in greater. 
# {{context|intransitive|obsolete|lang=en}} To be [[wont]].
#: {{rfquotek|Carew}}
# {{context|intransitive|obsolete|lang=en}} To [[cohabit]].
#* We with the best men '''accustom''' openly; you with the basest commit private adulteries. - [[w:John Milton|John Milton]]

